⁸⁴ Cum eo quartum coraule adolescemulas miles ad Capuam profectus sum, quintoque anno post ad Tarentum quoestor .- deinde aditis, quadri- enm'o pose factus sum ναίω-θ’ There is no doubt whatever that this reading is corrupt and interpolated, since it is at variance with the accounts both of ancient historiam and of Cicero himself. In the first place, Cato was not quaestor at the siege os Tarentum, but in Αἰτίοις nor under Fabius Maximae, but Scipio Africanus; and, moreover, so far was he from being a quaestor at the siege of the place in question, that he sei-ved on this occasion merely as a pri- vate soldier (miles). In the next place, there is no reason whatever why he should speak os himself, in this passage, as aedile and pne- tor, when his object is not to make any mention of himself, save only so far as will enable him to tell the praises of Fabius. Again, he did not fill the praetorship in the year when Tuditanus and Cethe- gus were consuls, but merely the office of quaestor, a fact of which Cicero himself is a witness. (Brut, 15, 6.) And, finally, he was not praetor four years aster his aedilesliip, but the very next year. We ought to have no hesitation, therefore, in rejecting oedilis and prator from the text, with Pighius (Annal. Rom, ad ann. 549, p. 219), and by a change of punctuation restoring his own to Cicero.
